     explicit array_t(size_t count, const T *ptr = nullptr, handle base = handle())
         : array(count, ptr, base) { }
 
+    std::vector<size_t> to_vect() {
+        return std::vector<size_t>();
+    }
+
+    template<typename I, typename... Ix> std::vector<size_t> to_vect(I i, Ix... rest) {
+        std::vector<size_t> s = to_vect(rest...);
+        s.push_back (i);
+        return s;
+    }
+
+    template<typename... Ix>  std::vector<size_t> to_vect1(Ix... rest) {
+        std::vector<size_t> s = to_vect(rest...);
+        std::reverse(s.begin(), s.end());
+        return s;
+    }
+
+    template<typename... Ix> explicit array_t(Ix... rest) : array_t (to_vect1 (rest...)) {}
+
     constexpr size_t itemsize() const {
         return sizeof(T);
     }
```

I wonder if this could be simplified by shifting most of the logic from the constructors into a kind of vector adaptor class. E.g., instead of:

```c++
template <typename Shape, typename Strides,
          typename = decltype(std::begin(std::declval<const Shape &>())),
          typename = decltype(std::begin(std::declval<const Strides &>()))>
 array(const Shape &shape, const Strides &strides);
```

use:

```c++
array(const Adaptor& shape, const Adaptor& strides);
```
where:
```c++
class Adaptor {
public:
    template <typename Container, typename /*= ... SFINAE*/>
    Adaptor(const Container& c);

private:
    std::vector<T> data; // or whatever
};
```

So instead of templating every constructor, the adaptor takes care of everything.

@andscoop I think @calvinwyoung was trying to update list views, not view the metadata - which is what issue #123 addresses. As far as I know, updating metadata can't be done with the REST API. 

According to Salesforce [documentation](https://developer.salesforce.com/docs/atlas.en-us.api_rest.meta/api_rest/using_resources_working_with_object_metadata.htm)

> [U]se REST API resources to retrieve object metadata information. For modifying or creating object metadata information, see the Metadata API Developer Guide.

